Type 2 Diabetes in Children--An Emerging Epidemic? Type 2 diabetes in children is itself a disease in its infancy.
The first reports of a high frequency of type 2 diabetes in adolescents appeared just 20 years ago, and much of the research that points to greater numbers of children and adolescents being diagnosed with type 2 diabetes has emerged only in the past 10 years.17 Recent studies indicate somewhere between eight and 45 percent of children with newly diagnosed diabetes have nonimmune-mediated diabetes, the majority of which are type 2 cases.
In a Cincinnati study, for example, type 2 diabetes comprised only two to four percent of all childhood diabetes before 1992.
By 1994, type 2 diabetes accounted for 16 percent of all new cases in children.
Among MexicanAmerican children studied in Ventura, California, 31 percent of those newly diagnosed with diabetes have type 2 diabetes.
Information from a study in San Antonio suggests that 40 percent of newly diagnosed children with diabetes are type 2.18 Differences in sampling methods and populations account for the varying results.19 To be sure, the number of is very small in relation to the Although Texas does not have studies and data collection are and to project the future effect children affected by type 2 diabetes (the prevalence) number of adults who have or will develop diabetes.
statistical data for a prevalence rate, epidemiological underway to identify the current impact of diabetes of type 2 diabetes among children.
However, case study reports may underestimate the true magnitude of the problem since they describe diagnosed cases only, according to the American Diabetes Association.
And due to the relatively recent recognition of type 2 diabetes in this age group, many children still may be misdiagnosed as having type 1 diabetes.20
