M
Aside from genetic factors, researchers are looking at changes in the living environment to help explain the surprising rise in type 2 diabetes in youth.
Physicians have noticed a definite trend in recent years: as children and teens have become less physically active and have gained weight, the number of children with type 2 diabetes has increased.
Most children with type 2 diabetes--up to 85 percent--are overweight, and virtually all studies suggest that obesity in children and adolescents plays a key role in early development of the disease.22 A lack of physical activity also is associated with type 2 diabetes.
According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, only one in four high school students participates in daily physical education classes.23
